In this press briefing, Press Secretary Jay Carney addresses questions about Afghanistan, the economy, the Susan G. Komen Foundation, and the controversy surrounding the HHS birth control decision. He clarifies the President's position on Afghanistan, stating that the goal is to transfer security lead to Afghan forces by the end of 2014, but that the pace and timing of the transition will be determined through ongoing discussions with NATO allies. Carney defends the President's economic policies, highlighting the progress made in job growth and economic recovery. He also defends the HHS birth control decision, stating that it is about ensuring access to healthcare for women and finding a balance between religious beliefs and providing necessary medical services. Carney dismisses calls for the resignation of Attorney General Eric Holder and emphasizes the administration's commitment to fighting criminal activity and illegal gun trafficking.